title: For Sale/Trade:  American made Mosin Nagants
postcontent: Located in the Longview / Kilgore, Tx. areaTwo largely unknown pieces of US WW1 history. Contracted by the Russian government and never honored do to the new politics after the Russian Revolution leaving Remington and Westinghouse on the hook over several million rifles and millions of dollars. These two rifles were actually delivered and issued. One is manufactured by Remington Armory (1917) and the other is New England Westinghouse (1915). Both are in good shape for their age and still in their original m1891 configuration. I have fired them and they still function well.The Reminton is a post WW1 arsenal refurb that has been refinished and action renumbered to the bolt. The Remington stamp is weak from the refurb process, but still legible. No import marks or any other stamps that don't belong. Finish is very nice minus some freckling and light handling wear. Displays very well. Bore is strong with good rifling, but a little dark. Two main issues are the missing cleaning rod and rear sight leaf spring is damaged. Both parts are still widely available online.The Westinghouse still retains it's original GI finish and walnut stock. It was later captured by Finland and has their "SA" stamp along with the renumbered sight graduations and sling swivels. It is fully intact and functions well for being 103 years old. It's a typical Finn mixmaster, but has all pre-1928 parts. Rifle is counterbored about 1/4 inch with strong rifling. Has an 80's era CAI import stamp on the bbl. Great piece of history and has the charachter to show it.Selling both as a package deal for $800. May consider trades of equal value or partial with cash.

title: For Sale:  U.S. South Carolina Militia issued Peabody Carbine/ SUPER RARE!!!
postcontent: PICTURE LINK: https://imgur.com/a/DGdIuUp for sale is a Peabody Carbine in caliber .50 Rimfire. This was made by Providence Tool Co in Providence, Rhode island. Most likely in 1871 (the very last ones were made in 1871). The serial number is 112657. If you do some research, you will find that there was a book written in 1978 that listed the highest serial number at that time ever recorded. It is about 40 numbers LOWER than this one. Here is the best part. This is one of 350 of these carbines shipped to the South Carolina militia in 1877. South Carolina started lettering the butt plates of the carbines in 1881. The ones that were still in service. So how many ACTUALLY remain today? I'm betting less than half the original number. Thus the S.C. marking on the top part of the butt plate. I have seen 3 others and the markings are identical. This carbine is 100% correct and original! Has some initials carved into the stock, looks like C.T. Rand to me. Could be the soldier who it was issued to. I figure I'll leave that geneology search to the buyer. If you can make some brass and reload some rounds for this, it is definitely still very shootable. Not sure if Buffalo Bore has ammo available for it or brass. One of these carbines sold at James D. Julia's auction in 2004 for $1,495. That's 14 years ago! $1,100 plus actual shipping or state tax in VT. Email me at REDACTED or call Shawn at REDACTED. ANTIQUE, SO NO FFL (EXCEPT WHERE REQUIRED). I DO REQUIRE A COPY OF YOUR ID.
